{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614086"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:41:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:41:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16341"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16341"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9032"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65211"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9032"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16341"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50648"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7507"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21484"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21487"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65211"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with sudden onset of painless vision loss in her right eye. The examining doctor performs fundoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical fundoscopic appearance of vitreous haemorrhage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bright red flame-shaped lesions","Yellow-white exudates","Copper wiring of arterioles","Dark red or black opacity obscuring retinal view","White cotton wool spots"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOn fundoscopic examination, \u003Cstrong\u003Edark red or black opacity obscuring the retinal view\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of vitreous haemorrhage. The opacity occurs because blood has leaked into the normally clear vitreous cavity, the clear gel that fills the space between the lens and the retina, blocking the examiner\u0027s view of the underlying retina. The hemoglobin in red blood cells absorbs and scatters light, making the hemorrhagic areas appear dark red however, over time, blood in the vitreous may clot. Clotted blood scatters light less efficiently, resulting in dark black or brown opacities on fundoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe appearance varies based on the extent and stage of the hemorrhage:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFresh hemorrhage: Typically appears dark red due to fresh, oxygenated blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOlder hemorrhage\u003Cstrong\u003E:\u003C/strong\u003E Becomes darker (black or brown) as the blood clots and degrades (hemoglobin is metabolized to hemosiderin).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other fundoscopic findings:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBright red flame-shaped lesions\u003C/strong\u003E are typical of superficial retinal haemorrhages\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhite cotton wool spots\u003C/strong\u003E represent areas of retinal ischaemia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYellow-white exudates\u003C/strong\u003E are seen in conditions like diabetic retinopathy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECopper wiring of arterioles\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with chronic hypertensive changes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe severity of visual symptoms in vitreous haemorrhage depends on the amount and location of bleeding. Small haemorrhages may appear as floaters, while dense haemorrhages can cause severe vision loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitreous haemorrhage appears as a dark red or black opacity that obscures the normal retinal view during fundoscopy.","The degree of visual loss in vitreous haemorrhage correlates with the density and location of the bleeding."],"references":["Shaikh N, Srishti R, Khanum A, Thirumalesh MB, Dave V, Arora A, Bansal R, Surve A, Azad S, Kumar V. Vitreous hemorrhage - Causes, diagnosis, and management. Indian J Ophthalmol. 2023 Jan;71(1):28-38. doi: 10.4103/ijo.IJO_928_22. PMID: 36588205; PMCID: PMC10155538.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50648"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16341"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50648"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T21:02:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T21:03:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9032"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65211"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","na